# Refined Solution
### Problem Statement Explanation
We have an adiabatic cylinder of cross-sectional area S, divided into two equal compartments of volume V0 each by an adiabatic, thin, lightweight, movable piston. Both compartments contain the same ideal monatomic gas (adiabatic index γ = 5/3). Initially:
- Left side (1): pressure p1(0) = 2p0, volume V1(0) = V0.
- Right side (2): pressure p2(0) = p0, volume V2(0) = V0.

The walls include a viscous element (negligible heat capacity and volume) that resists piston motion, dissipating mechanical energy into heat. At each moment, the dissipated heat is split equally between the two gases: δQ1 = δQ2 = (1/2) δW_diss. All processes are quasistatic (each gas remains in internal equilibrium; pressure is uniform on each side at any time; piston inertia is negligible).

The piston is released and moves to the right (since p1 > p2), eventually coming to rest (no static friction; viscous force vanishes at zero velocity). Let l > 0 be the final rightward displacement, so the final volumes are V1 = V0 + S l and V2 = V0 − S l. Define the dimensionless displacement x ≡ S l / V0 so that V1 = V0(1 + x), V2 = V0(1 − x). We must find l in the form l = x (V0/S), with x to two decimal places.

For the ideal monatomic gas with fixed amount on each side, the internal energy is U = pV/(γ − 1) = (3/2) pV.

### Step 1
Principles/Original Formulas/Assumptions:
\[
\boxed{dU_i = \delta Q_i - p_i\,dV_i \quad (i=1,2)\ \text{(First Law, quasistatic)}}
\]
\[
\boxed{U_i = \frac{p_i V_i}{\gamma - 1} \quad \text{with } \gamma = \frac{5}{3} \Rightarrow U_i = \frac{3}{2}\,p_i V_i}
\]
\[
\boxed{p_1 S - p_2 S - F_{\text{visc}} = 0 \quad \text{(quasistatic piston force balance)}}
\]
\[
\boxed{\delta W_{\text{diss}} = F_{\text{visc}}\,dl,\quad dV_1 = S\,dl,\quad dV_2 = -S\,dl}
\]
\[
\boxed{\delta Q_1 = \delta Q_2 = \tfrac{1}{2}\,\delta W_{\text{diss}} \quad \text{(equal heat split)}}
\]

Derivation:
\[
\begin{align}
&\text{From force balance:}\nonumber\\
F_{\text{visc}} &= S(p_1 - p_2).
\label{eq:Fvisc}\tag{1}
\end{align}
\]
\[
\begin{align}
&\text{Dissipation over } dl:\ \delta W_{\text{diss}} = F_{\text{visc}}\,dl = S(p_1 - p_2)\,dl
= p_1 dV_1 + p_2 dV_2.
\label{eq:Wdiss}\tag{2}
\end{align}
\]
\[
\begin{align}
&\text{First Law on each side with equal heat split:}\nonumber\\
dU_1 &= \tfrac{1}{2}\delta W_{\text{diss}} - p_1 dV_1
= -\tfrac{1}{2}p_1 dV_1 + \tfrac{1}{2}p_2 dV_2,
\label{eq:dU1}\tag{3}\\
dU_2 &= \tfrac{1}{2}\delta W_{\text{diss}} - p_2 dV_2
= \tfrac{1}{2}p_1 dV_1 - \tfrac{1}{2}p_2 dV_2.
\label{eq:dU2}\tag{4}
\end{align}
\]

### Step 2
Principles/Original Formulas/Assumptions:
\[
\boxed{d(U_1+U_2) = (\delta Q_1+\delta Q_2) - (p_1 dV_1 + p_2 dV_2)}
\]
\[
\boxed{U_i = \tfrac{3}{2} p_i V_i \Rightarrow dU_i = \tfrac{3}{2} d(p_i V_i)}
\]
\[
\boxed{\text{At final rest }(v=0):\ F_{\text{visc}}=0 \Rightarrow p_1 = p_2 \quad \text{(mechanical equilibrium)}}
\]

Derivation:
\[
\begin{align}
\delta Q_1+\delta Q_2 &= \delta W_{\text{diss}} \overset{\eqref{eq:Wdiss}}{=} p_1 dV_1 + p_2 dV_2
\Rightarrow d(U_1+U_2)=0 \Rightarrow U_1+U_2=\text{const}.
\label{eq:Uconst}\tag{5}
\end{align}
\]
\[
\begin{align}
U_1+U_2 &= \tfrac{3}{2}(p_1 V_1 + p_2 V_2) = \text{const}
\Rightarrow p_1 V_1 + p_2 V_2 = \text{const}.
\label{eq:sumconst}\tag{6}
\end{align}
\]
\[
\begin{align}
&\text{Initially: } p_1 V_1 + p_2 V_2 = 2p_0 V_0 + p_0 V_0 = 3 p_0 V_0.\nonumber\\
&\Rightarrow p_1 V_1 + p_2 V_2 = 3 p_0 V_0 \quad \text{for all times}. \nonumber\\
&\text{At final rest: } p_1=p_2=p_{\text{eq}},\ V_1+V_2=2V_0 \Rightarrow
p_{\text{eq}}(V_1+V_2) = 3 p_0 V_0 \Rightarrow p_{\text{eq}} = \tfrac{3}{2} p_0.
\label{eq:peq}\tag{7}
\end{align}
\]

### Step 3
Principles/Original Formulas/Assumptions:
\[
\boxed{dU_1 = \tfrac{3}{2}\,d(p_1 V_1)}
\]
\[
\boxed{d(p_1 V_1) = V_1\,dp_1 + p_1\,dV_1}
\]
\[
\boxed{p_2 V_2 = 3 p_0 V_0 - p_1 V_1 \quad \text{(from } \eqref{eq:sumconst}\text{)}}
\]

Derivation:
\[
\begin{align}
\tfrac{3}{2}d(p_1 V_1) &= dU_1 \overset{\eqref{eq:dU1}}{=}
-\tfrac{1}{2}p_1 dV_1 + \tfrac{1}{2}p_2 dV_2 \nonumber\\
\Rightarrow\ \tfrac{3}{2}(V_1 dp_1 + p_1 dV_1) &= -\tfrac{1}{2}p_1 dV_1 + \tfrac{1}{2}p_2 dV_2 \nonumber\\
\Rightarrow\ V_1\,dp_1 + \tfrac{4}{3}p_1\,dV_1 - \tfrac{1}{3}p_2\,dV_2 &= 0.
\label{eq:basic}\tag{8}
\end{align}
\]
\[
\begin{align}
&\text{Multiply \eqref{eq:basic} by } V_2 \text{ and use } p_2 V_2 = 3p_0V_0 - p_1 V_1:\nonumber\\
V_1 V_2\,dp_1 + \tfrac{4}{3} p_1 V_2\,dV_1 - \tfrac{1}{3}p_2 V_2\,dV_2 &= 0 \nonumber\\
\Rightarrow\ V_1 V_2\,dp_1 + \tfrac{4}{3} p_1 V_2\,dV_1 + \tfrac{1}{3} p_1 V_1\,dV_2 &= p_0 V_0\,dV_2.
\label{eq:preExact}\tag{9}
\end{align}
\]

### Step 4
Principles/Original Formulas/Assumptions:
\[
\boxed{d\!\left(p_1 V_1^{\alpha} V_2^{\beta}\right)
= V_1^{\alpha}V_2^{\beta}\,dp_1 + \alpha p_1 V_1^{\alpha-1}V_2^{\beta}\,dV_1 + \beta p_1 V_1^{\alpha}V_2^{\beta-1}\,dV_2}
\]

Derivation:
\[
\begin{align}
&\text{Choose } \alpha=\tfrac{4}{3},\ \beta=\tfrac{1}{3}. \text{ Multiply \eqref{eq:preExact} by } V_1^{1/3} V_2^{-2/3}:\nonumber\\
V_1^{4/3} V_2^{1/3}\,dp_1 + \tfrac{4}{3} p_1 V_1^{1/3} V_2^{1/3}\,dV_1 + \tfrac{1}{3} p_1 V_1^{4/3} V_2^{-2/3}\,dV_2 &= p_0 V_0\, V_1^{1/3} V_2^{-2/3}\,dV_2. \nonumber\\
&\text{The left-hand side is } d\!\left(p_1 V_1^{4/3} V_2^{1/3}\right). \ \text{Therefore,}
\label{eq:exactDiff}\tag{10}\\
d\!\left(p_1 V_1^{4/3} V_2^{1/3}\right) &= p_0 V_0\, V_1^{1/3} V_2^{-2/3}\,dV_2.
\label{eq:ode}\tag{11}
\end{align}
\]

### Step 5
Principles/Original Formulas/Assumptions:
\[
\boxed{V_1 = V_0(1+x),\quad V_2 = V_0(1-x),\quad dV_2 = -V_0\,dx}
\]
\[
\boxed{\text{Initial: } x=0,\ p_1=2p_0,\ V_1=V_2=V_0}
\]
\[
\boxed{\text{Final: } x=y,\ p_1=p_2=p_{\text{eq}}=\tfrac{3}{2}p_0,\ V_1=V_0(1+y),\ V_2=V_0(1-y)}
\]

Derivation:
\[
\begin{align}
&\text{Integrate \eqref{eq:ode} from initial }(x=0)\text{ to final }(x=y):\nonumber\\
&p_1(y)\,[V_0(1+y)]^{4/3}[V_0(1-y)]^{1/3} - p_1(0)\,V_0^{5/3} \nonumber\\
&\qquad= p_0 V_0 \int_{0}^{y} \left[V_0^{1/3}(1+x)^{1/3}\right]\left[V_0^{-2/3}(1-x)^{-2/3}\right]\,(-V_0\,dx) \nonumber\\
&\Rightarrow \Big(\tfrac{3}{2}p_0\Big) V_0^{5/3} (1+y)^{4/3}(1-y)^{1/3} - 2 p_0 V_0^{5/3} \nonumber\\
&\qquad= - p_0 V_0^{5/3} \int_{0}^{y} \frac{(1+x)^{1/3}}{(1-x)^{2/3}}\,dx \nonumber\\
&\Rightarrow \int_{0}^{y} \frac{(1+x)^{1/3}}{(1-x)^{2/3}}\,dx = 2 - \tfrac{3}{2}(1+y)^{4/3}(1-y)^{1/3}.
\label{eq:integralEq}\tag{12}
\end{align}
\]

### Step 6
Principles/Original Formulas/Assumptions:
\[
\boxed{F(y)\equiv \int_{0}^{y} \frac{(1+x)^{1/3}}{(1-x)^{2/3}}\,dx - \left[2 - \tfrac{3}{2}(1+y)^{4/3}(1-y)^{1/3}\right]=0}
\]
\[
\boxed{0<y<1 \quad \text{(to ensure } V_2=V_0(1-y)>0)}
\]

Derivation:
\[
\begin{align}
&\text{Evaluate both sides at } y=0.20:\ \int_{0}^{0.20} \frac{(1+x)^{1/3}}{(1-x)^{2/3}}\,dx \approx 0.2222, \nonumber\\
&\quad 2 - \tfrac{3}{2}(1.20)^{4/3}(0.80)^{1/3} \approx 0.2244,\ \Rightarrow F(0.20)\approx -2.2\times 10^{-3}.
\label{eq:checky}\tag{13}
\end{align}
\]
\[
\begin{align}
&\text{A single Newton update using } F'(y) = \frac{(1+y)^{1/3}}{(1-y)^{2/3}} + \tfrac{3}{2}\,\frac{d}{dy}\big[(1+y)^{4/3}(1-y)^{1/3}\big]\ \text{at } y=0.20 \text{ gives } y\approx 0.201.\nonumber\\
&\text{Hence, to two decimal places, } y = 0.20,\ \text{so } l = y\,\frac{V_0}{S} = 0.20\,\frac{V_0}{S}.
\label{eq:yfinal}\tag{14}
\end{align}
\]

### Final Answer
\[
\begin{align}
l = 0.20\,\frac{V_0}{S}
\end{align}
\]

# Refined Solution
### Problem Statement Explanation
We have a simple pendulum consisting of:
- A massless, insulating string of length α (we denote a = α).
- A thin, superconducting ring (circular loop) of mass m and radius r, with r ≪ a, attached to the free end of the string.

A static, uniform magnetic field of flux density B is present in a sector (wedge) whose center is at the suspension point (pivot). The sector edges are straight radial lines, and at the initial moment (θ = 0), the pendulum string is vertical and the ring lies just inside the sector: both sector edges are tangent to the ring. The magnetic field is perpendicular to the plane of the ring (into the page).

The ring is given an initial horizontal velocity of magnitude v0 (perpendicular to B). The magnetic field is sufficiently strong that, while the ring’s area overlaps the sector (i.e., while the ring is within the magnetic field region), the torque from the Ampère force greatly exceeds the gravitational torque; hence gravity can be neglected during that interval. Outside the field region, no magnetic force acts, but the superconducting current persists (no resistance), and the external flux through the ring remains constant (zero), so the current remains constant.

The superconducting ring has self-inductance L. Because initially the ring is at rest and fully inside a steady, spatially uniform magnetic field, we take the initial current I(0) = 0. The total linked flux L I + Φext is therefore conserved thereafter.

Definitions and geometry:
- θ: angular displacement of the pendulum from vertical downward.
- a: string length.
- r: ring radius (r ≪ a).
- θ0: small angle defined by sin θ0 = r/a.
- φ: geometric parameter for the circular segment cut by one sector edge in the ring’s disk; defined by r cos φ = d(θ), where d(θ) is the perpendicular distance from the ring center to the (near) sector edge. As θ increases from 0 to 2θ0, φ increases from 0 to π.
- S(θ): area of overlap between the ring’s disk and the magnetic sector; Φext(θ) = B S(θ).
- ω = dθ/dt: angular speed about the pivot.
- g: gravitational acceleration.

Approximations:
- r ≪ a ⇒ moment of inertia about the pivot Ipivot ≈ m a^2.
- While the ring overlaps the magnetic field (0 ≤ θ ≤ 2θ0), |τmag| ≫ |τgrav|, so gravity is neglected in this interval.
- Outside the field (θ ≥ 2θ0), Φext = 0 and magnetic forces vanish.

Goal: Find the minimum initial speed v0 such that the pendulum just reaches θ = π/2 (horizontal) with zero speed there.

### Step 1
Principles/Original Formulas/Assumptions:
\[
\boxed{\Phi_{\text{tot}} = L I + \Phi_{\text{ext}} = \text{constant} \quad \text{(flux conservation for a superconducting loop)}}
\]
\[
\boxed{\Phi_{\text{ext}}(\theta) = B\,S(\theta)}
\]
\[
\boxed{S(\theta) = \pi r^{2} - r^{2}\bigl(\phi - \sin\phi\,\cos\phi\bigr) \quad \text{(circle minus circular segment of half-angle }\phi\text{)}}
\]
\[
\boxed{\sin\theta_{0} = \frac{r}{a}, \qquad r\cos\phi = a\,\sin(\theta_{0}-\theta)}
\]

Derivation:
At θ = 0 the ring is fully inside the uniform field, I(0) = 0, so the conserved total flux equals the initial external flux:
\[
\begin{align}
\Phi_{\text{tot}} &= \Phi_{\text{ext}}(0) = B\,\pi r^{2}.
\label{eq:Phitot_init}\tag{1}
\end{align}
\]
While a single radial edge intersects the ring (0 ≤ θ ≤ 2θ0), the overlap area equals the full disk minus the circular segment cut by the edge. With the geometry relation r\cos\phi = a\sin(\theta_{0}-\theta),
\[
\begin{align}
L I + B\Bigl[\pi r^{2} - r^{2}\bigl(\phi - \sin\phi \cos\phi\bigr)\Bigr]
&= B\,\pi r^{2}.
\label{eq:flux_cons}\tag{2}
\end{align}
\]
Solving for I(φ),
\[
\begin{align}
I(\phi) &= \frac{B r^{2}}{L}\,\Bigl(\phi - \sin\phi \cos\phi\Bigr), \qquad 0\le \phi \le \pi.
\label{eq:Iphi}\tag{3}
\end{align}
\]
At exit (θ = 2θ0 ⇒ d = -r ⇒ φ = \pi), the overlap vanishes and
\[
\begin{align}
I_{\text{exit}} &= I(\pi) = \frac{\pi B r^{2}}{L}.
\label{eq:Iexit}\tag{4}
\end{align}
\]

### Step 2
Principles/Original Formulas/Assumptions:
\[
\boxed{P_{\text{mech}} = \tau_{\text{mag}}\,\omega = I\,\frac{d\Phi_{\text{ext}}}{dt}}
\]
\[
\boxed{\tau_{\text{mag}}(\theta) = I\,\frac{d\Phi_{\text{ext}}}{d\theta}}
\]
\[
\boxed{\frac{d}{d\phi}\Bigl[\phi - \sin\phi \cos\phi\Bigr] = 2\sin^{2}\phi}
\]
\[
\boxed{\frac{d\phi}{d\theta} = \frac{a}{r}\,\frac{\cos(\theta_{0}-\theta)}{\sin\phi}}
\]

Derivation:
Differentiate r\cos\phi = a\sin(\theta_{0}-\theta) to get
\[
\begin{align}
-r\sin\phi\,\frac{d\phi}{d\theta} &= a\cos(\theta_{0}-\theta)\,(-1)
\ \Rightarrow\
\frac{d\phi}{d\theta} = \frac{a}{r}\,\frac{\cos(\theta_{0}-\theta)}{\sin\phi}.
\label{eq:dphidtheta}\tag{5}
\end{align}
\]
Because Φext = B S(θ) with S(θ) = \pi r^{2} - r^{2}\bigl(\phi - \sin\phi\cos\phi\bigr),
\[
\begin{align}
\frac{d\Phi_{\text{ext}}}{d\theta}
&= B\,\frac{dS}{d\theta}
= -B r^{2}\,\frac{d}{d\phi}\!\Bigl(\phi - \sin\phi \cos\phi\Bigr)\,\frac{d\phi}{d\theta} \nonumber\\
&= -B r^{2}\,(2\sin^{2}\phi)\left(\frac{a}{r}\,\frac{\cos(\theta_{0}-\theta)}{\sin\phi}\right)
= -\,2 a r B\,\sin\phi\,\cos(\theta_{0}-\theta).
\label{eq:dPhidtheta}\tag{6}
\end{align}
\]
Hence the magnetic torque about the pivot is
\[
\begin{align}
\tau_{\text{mag}}(\theta) &= I\,\frac{d\Phi_{\text{ext}}}{d\theta}
= -\,2 a r B\,I\,\sin\phi\,\cos(\theta_{0}-\theta).
\label{eq:taumag}\tag{7}
\end{align}
\]

### Step 3
Principles/Original Formulas/Assumptions:
\[
\boxed{L\,\frac{dI}{dt} + \frac{d\Phi_{\text{ext}}}{dt} = 0 \quad \text{(flux conservation in time)}}
\]
\[
\boxed{\frac{d}{dt}\left(\frac{1}{2}L I^{2}\right) = L I\,\frac{dI}{dt}}
\]
\[
\boxed{\frac{d}{dt}\left(\frac{1}{2} m a^{2}\omega^{2}\right) = \tau_{\text{mag}}\,\omega}
\]

Derivation:
From L dI/dt + dΦext/dt = 0, multiplying by I gives
\[
\begin{align}
\frac{d}{dt}\left(\tfrac{1}{2} L I^{2}\right) &= L I\,\frac{dI}{dt} = -\,I\,\frac{d\Phi_{\text{ext}}}{dt}.
\label{eq:dUm}\tag{8}
\end{align}
\]
Using Pmech = τmag ω = I dΦext/dt,
\[
\begin{align}
\frac{d}{dt}\left(\tfrac{1}{2}L I^{2}\right) &= -\,\tau_{\text{mag}}\,\omega.
\label{eq:power}\tag{9}
\end{align}
\]
Neglecting gravity while the ring overlaps the field, the sum of mechanical kinetic energy and magnetic self-energy is conserved:
\[
\begin{align}
\frac{d}{dt}\left(\tfrac{1}{2} m a^{2}\omega^{2} + \tfrac{1}{2} L I^{2}\right) &= 0.
\label{eq:Ein}\tag{10}
\end{align}
\]
Between θ = 0 (I = 0, ω0 = v0/a) and θ = 2θ0 (I = Iexit, ω = ω2),
\[
\begin{align}
\tfrac{1}{2} m a^{2}\,\omega_{2}^{2} + \tfrac{1}{2} L I_{\text{exit}}^{2}
&= \tfrac{1}{2} m a^{2}\left(\frac{v_{0}}{a}\right)^{2}.
\label{eq:match}\tag{11}
\end{align}
\]
With Iexit from Eq. (4),
\[
\begin{align}
\omega_{2}^{2}
&= \frac{v_{0}^{2}}{a^{2}} - \frac{\pi^{2} B^{2} r^{4}}{m a^{2} L}.
\label{eq:omega2}\tag{12}
\end{align}
\]

### Step 4
Principles/Original Formulas/Assumptions:
\[
\boxed{U(\theta) - U(0) = m g a\,\bigl(1-\cos\theta\bigr)}
\]
\[
\boxed{\text{Outside field (}\theta\ge 2\theta_{0}\text{): } \tfrac{1}{2} m a^{2}\omega^{2} + U(\theta) = \text{constant}}
\]
\[
\boxed{\text{Minimum condition: reach } \theta=\tfrac{\pi}{2} \text{ with } \omega=0}
\]

Derivation:
Once outside the field (θ ≥ 2θ0), Φext = 0 is constant, the superconducting current I = Iexit is constant, and magnetic forces vanish. Thus only gravity changes the mechanical energy. For the minimal initial speed, the pendulum reaches θ = π/2 with zero speed, so the kinetic energy at exit must equal the required increase in gravitational potential from θ = 2θ0 to θ = π/2:
\[
\begin{align}
\frac{1}{2} m a^{2}\,\omega_{2}^{2}
&= U\!\left(\tfrac{\pi}{2}\right) - U(2\theta_{0}) \nonumber\\
&= m g a\left[\bigl(1 - \cos\tfrac{\pi}{2}\bigr) - \bigl(1 - \cos 2\theta_{0}\bigr)\right]
= m g a\,\cos(2\theta_{0}).
\label{eq:grav}\tag{13}
\end{align}
\]
Substitute Eq. (12) into Eq. (13):
\[
\begin{align}
\frac{1}{2} m a^{2}\left(\frac{v_{0}^{2}}{a^{2}} - \frac{\pi^{2} B^{2} r^{4}}{m a^{2} L}\right)
&= m g a\,\cos(2\theta_{0}) \\
\Rightarrow\quad
v_{0}^{2} &= 2 g a\,\cos(2\theta_{0}) + \frac{\pi^{2} B^{2} r^{4}}{m L}.
\label{eq:v0exact}\tag{14}
\end{align}
\]

### Step 5
Principles/Original Formulas/Assumptions:
\[
\boxed{\sin\theta_{0} = \frac{r}{a}\ll 1 \ \Rightarrow\ \cos(2\theta_{0}) = 1 - 2\sin^{2}\theta_{0} \simeq 1 - 2\left(\frac{r}{a}\right)^{2} \approx 1}
\]

Derivation:
Given r ≪ a, θ0 is small and cos(2θ0) ≈ 1 to leading order. Therefore Eq. (14) reduces to
\[
\begin{align}
v_{0}^{2} &\simeq 2 g a + \frac{\pi^{2} B^{2} r^{4}}{m L}.
\label{eq:v0approx}\tag{15}
\end{align}
\]

### Final Answer
\[
\begin{align}
v_{0} = \sqrt{2 g a + \frac{\pi^{2} B^{2} r^{4}}{m L}}
\end{align}
\]

# Refined Solution
### Problem Statement Explanation
We consider a general linear multi-terminal resistive network with N+1 terminals, where terminal 0 is designated as the reference (ground) with potential V0 = 0. For terminals i = 1, 2, …, N, their potentials Vi (relative to terminal 0) are linear functions of the terminal currents Ij (positive when flowing into the network, negative when flowing out), of the form Vi = ∑j aij Ij, with reciprocity aij = aji. The coefficients aij depend only on the network structure and not on the operating point; due to symmetry (reciprocity), the number of independent parameters is N(N+1)/2.

Specializing to a uniform square conductive thin plate as a four-terminal resistive network, the four corner terminals are labeled clockwise as 0, 1, 2, 3, with 0 as the reference. By the geometric symmetry of the square:
- The equivalent resistance between any adjacent pair of vertices (with the other two terminals open-circuited) is the same; denote this value by R1. In particular, R(0–1) = R(1–2) = R(2–3) = R(3–0) = R1.
- The equivalent resistance between any opposite pair of vertices (with the other two terminals open-circuited) is the same; denote this value by R2. In particular, R(0–2) = R(1–3) = R2.

Task: Using the aij-coefficient method, find the equivalent resistance between the remaining two vertices if a pair of adjacent vertices is short-circuited. Without loss of generality, we short terminals 3 and 0 (so V3 = V0 = 0) and compute the equivalent resistance between terminals 1 and 2 under that short.

Assumptions:
- Linearity and superposition hold for the resistive network.
- Reciprocity aij = aji holds.
- “Open-circuit” at a terminal means the current at that terminal is zero.
- “Short-circuit” between terminals p and q means Vp = Vq.

### Step 1
Principles/Original Formulas/Assumptions:
\[\boxed{V_i = \sum_{j=1}^{N} a_{ij}\, I_j \quad \text{with} \quad a_{ij}=a_{ji} \quad \text{(reciprocity)}}\]
\[\boxed{\text{Open terminal condition: } I_k=0 \ \text{at that terminal}}\]
\[\boxed{\text{Short circuit condition between nodes } p \text{ and } q: \ V_p=V_q}\]

Derivation:
Specialize to N = 3 (terminals 1, 2, 3; terminal 0 is the reference):
\[
\begin{align}
V_1 &= a_{11} I_1 + a_{12} I_2 + a_{13} I_3, \\
V_2 &= a_{21} I_1 + a_{22} I_2 + a_{23} I_3, \\
V_3 &= a_{31} I_1 + a_{32} I_2 + a_{33} I_3,
\tag{1}\label{eq:VAI}
\end{align}
\]
with aij = aji. By the square’s reflection symmetry about diagonal 0–2 (which swaps 1 ↔ 3 and fixes 0,2),
\[
\begin{align}
a_{11} = a_{33}, \quad a_{12} = a_{32}, \quad a_{21} = a_{23}.
\tag{2}\label{eq:symm}
\end{align}
\]

### Step 2
Principles/Original Formulas/Assumptions:
\[\boxed{R_{\mathrm{eq}} = \dfrac{V_{\mathrm{port}}}{I_{\mathrm{port}}} \ \text{(with all other terminals open-circuited)}}\]
\[\boxed{\text{Ohm’s law for the measured two-terminal port: } V = R_{\mathrm{eq}}\, I}\]

Derivation:
- Adjacent pair (0–1) with terminals 2 and 3 open: I1 = I, I2 = I3 = 0. Then V1 = a11 I, hence
\[
\begin{align}
R_1 = \frac{V_1}{I} = a_{11}.
\tag{3}\label{eq:a11}
\end{align}
\]
By symmetry 1 ↔ 3, a33 = a11 = R1.

- Opposite pair (0–2) with terminals 1 and 3 open: I2 = I, I1 = I3 = 0. Then V2 = a22 I, hence
\[
\begin{align}
R_2 = \frac{V_2}{I} = a_{22}.
\tag{4}\label{eq:a22}
\end{align}
\]
Thus,
\[
\begin{align}
a_{11} = a_{33} = R_1,\qquad a_{22} = R_2.
\tag{5}\label{eq:diag}
\end{align}
\]

### Step 3
Principles/Original Formulas/Assumptions:
\[\boxed{\text{By square symmetry: } R_{\mathrm{eq}}(1\text{–}2;\ 0,3\ \text{open}) = R_1}\]
\[\boxed{\text{Linearity/Superposition: } V = A I \ \Rightarrow \ \text{take } (I_1,I_2,I_3) = (I,-I,0)}\]

Derivation:
Measure the equivalent resistance between adjacent vertices 1 and 2 with 0 and 3 open. Drive I1 = I, I2 = −I, I3 = 0. From Eq. \eqref{eq:VAI},
\[
\begin{align}
V_1 &= a_{11} I + a_{12}(-I) = (a_{11} - a_{12}) I, \\
V_2 &= a_{21} I + a_{22}(-I) = (a_{12} - a_{22}) I.
\tag{6}\label{eq:V12adj}
\end{align}
\]
Hence the voltage between 1 and 2 is
\[
\begin{align}
V_1 - V_2 = \big(a_{11} - 2 a_{12} + a_{22}\big) I.
\tag{7}\label{eq:Vdrop12}
\end{align}
\]
By symmetry this equals R1 I, so
\[
\begin{align}
R_1 = a_{11} - 2 a_{12} + a_{22}.
\tag{8}\label{eq:R1rel}
\end{align}
\]
Using Eq. \eqref{eq:diag}, we obtain
\[
\begin{align}
a_{12} = \frac{R_2}{2}.
\tag{9}\label{eq:a12}
\end{align}
\]
By Eq. \eqref{eq:symm}, a21 = a23 = a32 = a12 = R2/2.

### Step 4
Principles/Original Formulas/Assumptions:
\[\boxed{\text{By square symmetry: } R_{\mathrm{eq}}(1\text{–}3;\ 0,2\ \text{open}) = R_2}\]
\[\boxed{\text{Linearity/Superposition: } V = A I \ \Rightarrow \ \text{take } (I_1,I_3) = (I,-I),\ I_2=0}\]

Derivation:
Measure the equivalent resistance between opposite vertices 1 and 3 with 0 and 2 open. Drive I1 = I, I3 = −I, I2 = 0. Then
\[
\begin{align}
V_1 &= a_{11} I + a_{13}(-I) = (a_{11} - a_{13}) I, \\
V_3 &= a_{31} I + a_{33}(-I) = (a_{13} - a_{33}) I,
\tag{10}\label{eq:V13opp}
\end{align}
\]
so
\[
\begin{align}
V_1 - V_3 = \big(a_{11} - 2 a_{13} + a_{33}\big) I.
\tag{11}\label{eq:Vdrop13}
\end{align}
\]
Equating to R2 I and using a11 = a33 = R1 from Eq. \eqref{eq:diag} gives
\[
\begin{align}
R_2 = 2 R_1 - 2 a_{13} \ \Rightarrow \ a_{13} = R_1 - \frac{R_2}{2}.
\tag{12}\label{eq:a13}
\end{align}
\]
We have now
\[
\begin{align}
a_{11}=a_{33}=R_1,\quad a_{22}=R_2,\quad a_{12}=a_{21}=a_{23}=a_{32}=\frac{R_2}{2},\quad a_{13}=a_{31}=R_1-\frac{R_2}{2}.
\tag{13}\label{eq:allA}
\end{align}
\]

### Step 5
Principles/Original Formulas/Assumptions:
\[\boxed{\text{Short 3 to 0: } V_3 = V_0 = 0}\]
\[\boxed{\text{Two-terminal drive between 1 and 2: } I_1=I,\ I_2=-I,\ \text{and } I_3 \text{ adjusts to enforce } V_3=0}\]

Derivation:
To find the equivalent resistance between 1 and 2 with 3 shorted to 0, drive a current I into terminal 1 and extract I at terminal 2, letting I3 = I′ be determined by V3 = 0:
\[
\begin{align}
I_1 = I,\quad I_2 = -I,\quad I_3 = I'.
\tag{14}\label{eq:drive}
\end{align}
\]
From Eq. \eqref{eq:VAI} and coefficients \eqref{eq:allA},
\[
\begin{align}
V_3 &= a_{31} I_1 + a_{32} I_2 + a_{33} I_3 \\
&= \left(R_1-\frac{R_2}{2}\right) I + \left(\frac{R_2}{2}\right)(-I) + R_1 I' \\
&= (R_1 - R_2) I + R_1 I'.
\tag{15}\label{eq:V3expr}
\end{align}
\]
The short requires V3 = 0, hence
\[
\begin{align}
0 = (R_1 - R_2) I + R_1 I' \ \Rightarrow \ I' = \frac{R_2 - R_1}{R_1}\, I.
\tag{16}\label{eq:Iprime}
\end{align}
\]

### Step 6
Principles/Original Formulas/Assumptions:
\[\boxed{R_{\mathrm{eq}}(1\text{–}2;\ 3 \text{ shorted to } 0) = \dfrac{V_1 - V_2}{I}}\]
\[\boxed{\text{Use } V = A I \ \text{with the coefficients from Eq. } \eqref{eq:allA}}\]

Derivation:
Compute V1 and V2 under \eqref{eq:drive}:
\[
\begin{align}
V_1 &= a_{11} I_1 + a_{12} I_2 + a_{13} I' 
= R_1 I - \left(\frac{R_2}{2}\right) I + \left(R_1 - \frac{R_2}{2}\right) I' \\
&= \left(R_1 - \frac{R_2}{2}\right) I + \left(R_1 - \frac{R_2}{2}\right) I',
\tag{17}\label{eq:V1}
\\
V_2 &= a_{21} I_1 + a_{22} I_2 + a_{23} I'
= \left(\frac{R_2}{2}\right) I - R_2 I + \left(\frac{R_2}{2}\right) I' \\
&= -\left(\frac{R_2}{2}\right) I + \left(\frac{R_2}{2}\right) I'.
\tag{18}\label{eq:V2}
\end{align}
\]
Therefore,
\[
\begin{align}
V_1 - V_2 
&= \left(R_1 - \frac{R_2}{2}\right) I + \left(R_1 - \frac{R_2}{2}\right) I' + \left(\frac{R_2}{2}\right) I - \left(\frac{R_2}{2}\right) I' \\
&= R_1 I + (R_1 - R_2) I'.
\tag{19}\label{eq:Vdiff}
\end{align}
\]
Substitute Eq. \eqref{eq:Iprime}:
\[
\begin{align}
V_1 - V_2 
&= R_1 I + (R_1 - R_2)\left(\frac{R_2 - R_1}{R_1}\right) I \\
&= \left[ R_1 - \frac{(R_1 - R_2)^2}{R_1} \right] I
= \frac{2 R_1 R_2 - R_2^2}{R_1}\, I
= \frac{R_2 (2 R_1 - R_2)}{R_1}\, I.
\tag{20}\label{eq:VdiffFinal}
\end{align}
\]
Hence,
\[
\begin{align}
R_{\mathrm{eq}}(1\text{–}2;\ 3 \parallel 0) = \frac{V_1 - V_2}{I} = \frac{R_2 (2 R_1 - R_2)}{R_1}.
\tag{21}\label{eq:ReqFinal}
\end{align}
\]
By symmetry, this is the same result for any choice of the shorted adjacent pair and the remaining two vertices.

### Final Answer
\[
\begin{align}
\boxed{R_{\mathrm{eq}} \;=\; \dfrac{R_2\,\big(2 R_1 - R_2\big)}{R_1}}
\end{align}
\]

# Refined Solution
### Problem Statement Explanation
We consider the following setup:
- A semi-infinite, tightly wound solenoid of radius R, with turns per unit length n, driven by an ideal current source that maintains a constant current I. Its axis is the z-axis. The solenoid extends from z = 0 to z = −∞. The winding direction is counterclockwise when viewed from +z, so the solenoid’s magnetic field points in the +z direction just above the open end (z > 0).
- A thin superconducting ring (current loop) of radius r with r ≪ R, mass m (uniform density), and self-inductance L. The loop’s symmetry axis is constrained to coincide with the z-axis, and it can move freely along z. Gravitational acceleration is g⃗ = −g ẑ.
- At the instant the ring transitions to the superconducting state, a current I0 flows in the loop in the +θ̂ direction. Far from the solenoid (z → +∞), there is no other external magnetic field (so the external flux there is negligible). After the transition, the loop remains superconducting, hence its fluxoid is conserved.
- Let z0 > 0 be the equilibrium height (if the equilibrium is stable). We are to find the period T of small vertical oscillations about z0. The final expression should be in terms of n, I0, r, R, L, m, and may include z0. The solenoid current I is fixed by the current source.

Assumptions:
- r ≪ R so the solenoid’s on-axis field is approximately uniform across the loop’s area; thus Φext ≈ A B(z) with A = π r^2.
- Quasi-static motion without dissipation; the superconducting loop has zero resistance and maintains fluxoid conservation.
- The solenoid current I is constant (ideal current source), so its field B(z) is a prescribed function of z; back-reaction on I is neglected.

### Step 1
Principles/Original Formulas/Assumptions:
\[
\boxed{\text{Biot–Savart law: on-axis field of a circular loop of radius }R:\;\; B_{\text{loop}}(z)=\frac{\mu_0 I R^2}{2\,(R^2+z^2)^{3/2}}}
\]
\[
\boxed{\text{Superposition for a continuous winding:}\;\; B_{\text{sol}}(z)=\int \! n\, B_{\text{loop}}(z+s)\, ds}
\]
\[
\boxed{\text{On-axis field of a semi-infinite solenoid for }z>0:\;\; B(z)=\frac{\mu_0 n I}{2}\Big(1-\frac{z}{\sqrt{z^2+R^2}}\Big)}
\]

Derivation:
\[
\begin{align}
B(z)
&= \int_{s=0}^{\infty} n \,\frac{\mu_0 I R^2}{2\,[R^2+(z+s)^2]^{3/2}}\, ds
\label{eq:semiint-start}\tag{1}\\
&= \frac{\mu_0 n I R^2}{2}\int_{u=z}^{\infty}\frac{du}{[R^2+u^2]^{3/2}}
\qquad (u=z+s)
\label{eq:changevar}\tag{2}\\
&= \frac{\mu_0 n I R^2}{2} \left[\frac{u}{R^2\sqrt{R^2+u^2}}\right]_{u=z}^{u\to\infty}
= \frac{\mu_0 n I}{2}\left(1-\frac{z}{\sqrt{z^2+R^2}}\right).
\label{eq:semiinfiniteB}\tag{3}
\end{align}
\]

### Step 2
Principles/Original Formulas/Assumptions:
\[
\boxed{\text{Fluxoid conservation for a superconducting loop:}\;\; L I(z) + \Phi_{\text{ext}}(z) = \text{const}}
\]
\[
\boxed{\text{External flux for a small loop:}\;\; \Phi_{\text{ext}}(z) \simeq A\,B(z),\quad A=\pi r^2}
\]
\[
\boxed{\text{Initial condition (far from solenoid):}\;\; \Phi_{\text{ext}}(\infty)\approx 0,\; I(\infty)=I_0\;\Rightarrow\; L I(z)+A B(z)=L I_0}
\]

Derivation:
\[
\begin{align}
L I(z) + \Phi_{\text{ext}}(z) &= L I_0
\label{eq:fluxoid}\tag{4}\\
\Rightarrow\quad I(z) &= I_0 - \frac{\Phi_{\text{ext}}(z)}{L}
= I_0 - \frac{A}{L} B(z).
\label{eq:Iz}\tag{5}
\end{align}
\]

### Step 3
Principles/Original Formulas/Assumptions:
\[
\boxed{\text{Magnetic energy stored in the loop:}\;\; U_{\text{loop}}=\frac{1}{2}L I^2}
\]
\[
\boxed{\text{Using }L I = L I_0 - \Phi_{\text{ext}}:\;\; U(z)=\frac{[L I_0-\Phi_{\text{ext}}(z)]^2}{2L}}
\]
\[
\boxed{\text{Conservative force from a potential:}\;\; F_z = -\frac{dU}{dz}}
\]

Derivation:
\[
\begin{align}
U(z) &= \frac{[L I_0 - \Phi_{\text{ext}}(z)]^2}{2L}
\label{eq:Uz}\tag{6}\\
\frac{dU}{dz} &= \frac{1}{L}[L I_0 - \Phi_{\text{ext}}(z)]\left(-\frac{d\Phi_{\text{ext}}}{dz}\right)
= -\frac{1}{L}[L I_0 - \Phi_{\text{ext}}(z)]\, \Phi_{\text{ext}}'(z)
\label{eq:dUdz}\tag{7}\\
\Rightarrow\; F_z(z) &= -\frac{dU}{dz}
= \frac{1}{L}\,[L I_0 - \Phi_{\text{ext}}(z)]\, \Phi_{\text{ext}}'(z)
= A\,B'(z)\,\Big[I_0 - \frac{A}{L} B(z)\Big].
\label{eq:Fz1}\tag{8}
\end{align}
\]
From Step 1, with B(z)=\frac{\mu_0 n I}{2}\left(1-\frac{z}{\sqrt{z^2+R^2}}\right),
\[
\begin{align}
B'(z) &= \frac{\mu_0 n I}{2}\,\frac{d}{dz}\!\left(1-\frac{z}{\sqrt{z^2+R^2}}\right)
= \frac{\mu_0 n I}{2}\left[-\frac{R^2}{(z^2+R^2)^{3/2}}\right]
= -\frac{\mu_0 n I R^2}{2\,(z^2+R^2)^{3/2}}.
\label{eq:Bprime}\tag{9}
\end{align}
\]
Insert A=\pi r^2 and define A_0:=\frac{\pi}{2}\mu_0 n I R^2 r^2 and C:=\frac{\mu_0 n I \pi r^2}{2L}. Then
\[
\begin{align}
F_z(z) &= \left(\pi r^2\right)\!\left[-\frac{\mu_0 n I R^2}{2\,(z^2+R^2)^{3/2}}\right]\!\left[I_0 - \frac{\pi r^2}{L} B(z)\right]
\label{eq:Fz2}\tag{10}\\
&= \frac{\pi}{2}\,\mu_0 n I R^2 r^2 \,\frac{1}{(z^2+R^2)^{3/2}}
\left[\frac{\mu_0 n I \pi r^2}{2L}\left(1-\frac{z}{\sqrt{z^2+R^2}}\right) - I_0 \right]
\equiv A_0\,(z^2+R^2)^{-3/2}\!\left[C\!\left(1-\frac{z}{\sqrt{z^2+R^2}}\right)-I_0\right].
\label{eq:Fz3}\tag{11}
\end{align}
\]

### Step 4
Principles/Original Formulas/Assumptions:
\[
\boxed{\text{Static equilibrium (ẑ upward):}\;\; \sum F_z = 0\;\Rightarrow\; F_z(z_0) - mg = 0}
\]

Derivation:
\[
\begin{align}
F_z(z_0) &= mg
\label{eq:equil}\tag{12}\\
\frac{\pi}{2}\,\mu_0 n I R^2 r^2 \,\frac{1}{(z_0^2+R^2)^{3/2}}
\left[\frac{\mu_0 n I \pi r^2}{2L}\left(1-\frac{z_0}{\sqrt{z_0^2+R^2}}\right) - I_0 \right]
&= mg.
\label{eq:equil-explicit}\tag{13}
\end{align}
\]

### Step 5
Principles/Original Formulas/Assumptions:
\[
\boxed{\text{Linearization near equilibrium:}\;\; m\,\ddot{\delta z} \simeq \left.\frac{dF_z}{dz}\right|_{z_0}\delta z}
\]
\[
\boxed{\text{Stability criterion:}\;\; \left.\frac{dF_z}{dz}\right|_{z_0} < 0}
\]
\[
\boxed{\text{Small-oscillation period:}\;\; T = 2\pi\sqrt{\frac{m}{-\left.\frac{dF_z}{dz}\right|_{z_0}}}}
\]

Derivation:
With A_0 and C as in Eq. (11),
\[
\begin{align}
F_z(z) &= A_0\, (z^2+R^2)^{-3/2}\,\Big[C\!\left(1-\frac{z}{\sqrt{z^2+R^2}}\right)-I_0\Big].
\label{eq:Fz-compact}\tag{14}
\end{align}
\]
Using
\[
\frac{d}{dz}(z^2+R^2)^{-3/2}=-\frac{3z}{(z^2+R^2)^{5/2}},\qquad
\frac{d}{dz}\!\left(1-\frac{z}{\sqrt{z^2+R^2}}\right)=-\frac{R^2}{(z^2+R^2)^{3/2}},
\]
we find
\[
\begin{align}
\frac{dF_z}{dz}
&= A_0\Bigg[
-\frac{3z}{(z^2+R^2)^{5/2}}\Big(C\!\left(1-\frac{z}{\sqrt{z^2+R^2}}\right)-I_0\Big)
- \frac{C R^2}{(z^2+R^2)^3}
\Bigg]
\label{eq:dFdz-raw}\tag{15}\\
&= A_0\left[
-\frac{3z(C-I_0)}{(z^2+R^2)^{5/2}}
+ C\,\frac{3 z^2 - R^2}{(z^2+R^2)^3}
\right].
\label{eq:dFdz-final}\tag{16}
\end{align}
\]
Evaluated at z=z0:
\[
\begin{align}
\left.\frac{dF_z}{dz}\right|_{z_0}
= \frac{\pi}{2}\mu_0 n I R^2 r^2\left[
-\frac{3z_0}{(z_0^2+R^2)^{5/2}}\left(\frac{\mu_0 n I \pi r^2}{2L}-I_0\right)
+ \frac{\mu_0 n I \pi r^2}{2L}\,\frac{3 z_0^2 - R^2}{(z_0^2+R^2)^3}
\right].
\label{eq:dFdz-z0}\tag{17}
\end{align}
\]
Stability requires dF_z/dz|_{z0} < 0, which can be rearranged as
\[
\begin{align}
\frac{\mu_0 n I \pi r^2}{2L}\,\frac{3 z_0^2 - R^2}{\sqrt{z_0^2+R^2}}
< 3 z_0\left(\frac{\mu_0 n I \pi r^2}{2L}-I_0\right),
\label{eq:stab1}\tag{18}
\end{align}
\]
or explicitly,
\[
\begin{align}
\frac{3 z_0^2 - R^2}{3 z_0 \sqrt{z_0^2+R^2}}
< 1 - \frac{2 I_0 L}{\mu_0 n I \pi r^2}.
\label{eq:stability-criterion}\tag{19}
\end{align}
\]
With k := -\left.\frac{dF_z}{dz}\right|_{z_0} > 0, the period of small oscillations is
\[
\begin{align}
T
&= 2\pi\sqrt{\frac{m}{k}}
= 2\pi\sqrt{\frac{m}{-\left.\frac{dF_z}{dz}\right|_{z_0}}}
\label{eq:T-generic}\tag{20}\\
&= 2\pi\sqrt{
\frac{m}{
\frac{\pi}{2}\mu_0 n I R^2 r^2\left[
\left(\frac{\mu_0 n I \pi r^2}{2L}-I_0\right)\frac{3 z_0}{(z_0^2+R^2)^{5/2}}
-\frac{\mu_0 n I \pi r^2}{2L}\,\frac{3 z_0^2 - R^2}{(z_0^2+R^2)^3}
\right]
}
}.
\label{eq:T-final}\tag{21}
\end{align}
\]

### Final Answer
\[
\begin{align}
\text{Stability condition:}\quad
\frac{3 z_0^2 - R^2}{3 z_0 \sqrt{z_0^2+R^2}}
< 1 - \frac{2 I_0 L}{\mu_0 n I \pi r^2},
\quad (z_0>0);\qquad
T
= 2\pi\sqrt{
\frac{m}{
\frac{\pi}{2}\mu_0 n I R^2 r^2\left[
\left(\frac{\mu_0 n I \pi r^2}{2L}-I_0\right)\frac{3 z_0}{(z_0^2+R^2)^{5/2}}
-\frac{\mu_0 n I \pi r^2}{2L}\,\frac{3 z_0^2 - R^2}{(z_0^2+R^2)^3}
\right]
}
}.
\end{align}
\]

# Refined Solution
### Problem Statement Explanation
We consider a parallel-plate structure of area A filled by two planar dielectric layers in series between perfectly conducting electrodes. The plate separation is h1 + h2. The first layer has thickness h1, permittivity ε1, and conductivity σ1; the second has thickness h2, permittivity ε2, and conductivity σ2. At t = 0, an ideal DC source with electromotive force U0 is connected across the plates. The capacitor is initially uncharged. The task is to find the time-dependent current I(t) through the switch (the same as through the series stack) for t > 0.

Definitions and modeling assumptions:
- E1(t), E2(t): uniform electric fields in layers 1 and 2 (normal to the plates).
- D1 = ε1 E1, D2 = ε2 E2: electric flux densities in the two layers.
- j1 = σ1 E1, j2 = σ2 E2: conduction current densities in the two layers.
- J(t): total current density through the stack; in 1D series geometry J is the same in both layers and equals conduction plus displacement current locally.
- σ(t): free surface charge density at the interface between the two dielectrics; sign convention consistent with σ = n·(D2 − D1) for a normal n from medium 1 to 2.
- The plates are ideal conductors; fringe effects are neglected; fields are uniform in each layer (large-area approximation).
- Initially uncharged means all free charges (including interfacial σ) are zero at t = 0−; we take σ(0) = 0.

We seek I(t) = A J(t) for t > 0.

### Step 1
Principles/Original Formulas/Assumptions:
\[
\boxed{V=\int_{\text{path}} \mathbf{E}\cdot d\mathbf{\ell} \;\Rightarrow\; h_1 E_1 + h_2 E_2 = U_0}
\]
\[
\boxed{\mathbf{D}=\varepsilon \mathbf{E}}
\]
\[
\boxed{\mathbf{j}_{\text{cond}}=\sigma \mathbf{E}}
\]
\[
\boxed{\mathbf{J}_{\text{total}}=\mathbf{j}_{\text{cond}}+\frac{\partial \mathbf{D}}{\partial t}}
\]
\[
\boxed{\sigma_{\text{free, interface}}=\hat{\mathbf{n}}\cdot(\mathbf{D}_2-\mathbf{D}_1)}
\]
\[
\boxed{\frac{d\sigma}{dt}=j_{1,\perp}-j_{2,\perp}}
\]

Derivation:
\[
\begin{align}
&\text{Applied voltage across the stack:} \quad h_1 E_1(t)+h_2 E_2(t)=U_0
\label{eq:V} \tag{1}\\
&\text{Constitutive relations:} \quad D_k=\varepsilon_k E_k,\; j_k=\sigma_k E_k\quad (k=1,2) \nonumber\\
&\text{Total current density (same through both layers):} \quad
J(t)=\sigma_1 E_1+\varepsilon_1 \frac{dE_1}{dt}=\sigma_2 E_2+\varepsilon_2 \frac{dE_2}{dt}
\label{eq:Jdef} \tag{2}\\
&\text{Interfacial free charge density:} \quad \sigma(t)=\varepsilon_2 E_2(t)-\varepsilon_1 E_1(t)
\label{eq:sigmadef} \tag{3}\\
&\text{Charge continuity at the interface (normal currents):} \quad \frac{d\sigma}{dt}=\sigma_1 E_1(t)-\sigma_2 E_2(t)
\label{eq:cont} \tag{4}
\end{align}
\]

### Step 2
Principles/Original Formulas/Assumptions:
\[
\boxed{\text{Cramer's rule for solving a 2\times 2 linear system}}
\]

Derivation:
\[
\begin{align}
&\text{Use \eqref{eq:sigmadef} and \eqref{eq:V} to solve for }E_1,E_2\text{ in terms of }\sigma. \nonumber\\
&\text{Write the system: } 
\begin{cases}
-\varepsilon_1 E_1+\varepsilon_2 E_2=\sigma\\
h_1 E_1+h_2 E_2=U_0
\end{cases} \nonumber\\
&\text{Define } a\equiv \varepsilon_1 h_2+\varepsilon_2 h_1. \label{eq:a} \tag{5}\\
&\Rightarrow\;
E_1(t)=\frac{\varepsilon_2 U_0-\sigma(t) h_2}{a}, 
\qquad
E_2(t)=\frac{\varepsilon_1 U_0+\sigma(t) h_1}{a}.
\label{eq:Eofsigma} \tag{6}
\end{align}
\]

### Step 3
Principles/Original Formulas/Assumptions:
\[
\boxed{\text{First-order linear ODE solution: } \frac{dy}{dt}+p\,y=q \;\Rightarrow\; y(t)=y_\infty+\big(y(0)-y_\infty\big)e^{-pt}}
\]

Derivation:
\[
\begin{align}
&\text{Insert \eqref{eq:Eofsigma} into the continuity equation \eqref{eq:cont}:} \nonumber\\
\frac{d\sigma}{dt}
&=\sigma_1 \frac{\varepsilon_2 U_0-\sigma h_2}{a}-\sigma_2 \frac{\varepsilon_1 U_0+\sigma h_1}{a} \nonumber\\
&=\frac{(\sigma_1 \varepsilon_2-\sigma_2 \varepsilon_1)U_0-(\sigma_1 h_2+\sigma_2 h_1)\sigma}{a}.
\label{eq:ODEsigma} \tag{7}
\end{align}
\]
Define
\[
\begin{align}
b \equiv \sigma_1 h_2 + \sigma_2 h_1, 
\qquad
\tau \equiv \frac{a}{b}=\frac{\varepsilon_1 h_2+\varepsilon_2 h_1}{\sigma_1 h_2+\sigma_2 h_1}.
\label{eq:btau} \tag{8}
\end{align}
\]
Then
\[
\begin{align}
\frac{d\sigma}{dt}+\frac{b}{a}\sigma=\frac{(\sigma_1 \varepsilon_2-\sigma_2 \varepsilon_1)}{a}\,U_0.
\label{eq:ODElin} \tag{9}
\end{align}
\]
With σ(0)=0 (initially uncharged), the solution is
\[
\begin{align}
\sigma(t)=\sigma_\infty \big(1-e^{-t/\tau}\big), 
\qquad
\sigma_\infty=\frac{U_0(\sigma_1 \varepsilon_2-\sigma_2 \varepsilon_1)}{b}.
\label{eq:sigsol} \tag{10}
\end{align}
\]

### Step 4
Principles/Original Formulas/Assumptions:
\[
\boxed{J(t)=\sigma_1 E_1+\varepsilon_1 \frac{dE_1}{dt}=\sigma_2 E_2+\varepsilon_2 \frac{dE_2}{dt}}
\]
\[
\boxed{I(t)=A\,J(t)}
\]

Derivation:
\[
\begin{align}
&\text{From \eqref{eq:Eofsigma}, }E_1(t)=\frac{\varepsilon_2 U_0}{a}-\frac{h_2}{a}\sigma(t)
\;\Rightarrow\;
\frac{dE_1}{dt}=-\frac{h_2}{a}\frac{d\sigma}{dt}.
\label{eq:dE1} \tag{11}
\end{align}
\]
Hence
\[
\begin{align}
J(t)
&=\sigma_1 E_1+\varepsilon_1 \frac{dE_1}{dt}
=\sigma_1 \frac{\varepsilon_2 U_0-\sigma h_2}{a}
-\varepsilon_1 \frac{h_2}{a}\frac{d\sigma}{dt} \nonumber\\
&=\underbrace{\left[\frac{\sigma_1 \varepsilon_2 U_0}{a}-\frac{\sigma_1 h_2}{a}\sigma_\infty\right]}_{J_\infty}
+\left[\frac{\sigma_1 h_2}{a}\sigma_\infty-\frac{\varepsilon_1 h_2}{a}\frac{\sigma_\infty}{\tau}\right] e^{-t/\tau},
\quad\text{using \eqref{eq:sigsol}.}
\label{eq:Jsplit} \tag{12}
\end{align}
\]
The steady current density simplifies to
\[
\begin{align}
J_\infty=\frac{U_0 \sigma_1 \sigma_2}{b},
\label{eq:Jinf} \tag{13}
\end{align}
\]
which matches the series conduction result. For the exponential amplitude, use
\[
\begin{align}
\sigma_1-\frac{\varepsilon_1}{\tau}
=\sigma_1-\frac{\varepsilon_1 b}{a}
=\frac{\sigma_1 a-\varepsilon_1 b}{a}
=\frac{h_1 (\sigma_1 \varepsilon_2-\sigma_2 \varepsilon_1)}{a},
\label{eq:identity} \tag{14}
\end{align}
\]
to obtain
\[
\begin{align}
\left[\frac{\sigma_1 h_2}{a}\sigma_\infty-\frac{\varepsilon_1 h_2}{a}\frac{\sigma_\infty}{\tau}\right]
&=\frac{h_2 \sigma_\infty}{a}\left(\sigma_1-\frac{\varepsilon_1}{\tau}\right)
=\frac{h_2 \sigma_\infty}{a}\cdot \frac{h_1 (\sigma_1 \varepsilon_2-\sigma_2 \varepsilon_1)}{a} \nonumber\\
&=\frac{U_0(\sigma_1 \varepsilon_2-\sigma_2 \varepsilon_1)^2 h_1 h_2}{a^2 b}.
\label{eq:amplitude} \tag{15}
\end{align}
\]
Therefore,
\[
\begin{align}
J(t)=\frac{U_0 \sigma_1 \sigma_2}{b}
+\frac{U_0(\sigma_1 \varepsilon_2-\sigma_2 \varepsilon_1)^2 h_1 h_2}{a^2 b}\,e^{-t/\tau},
\qquad I(t)=A\,J(t).
\label{eq:Jfinal} \tag{16}
\end{align}
\]

### Step 5
Principles/Original Formulas/Assumptions:
\[
\boxed{\lim_{t\to\infty} e^{-t/\tau}=0,\quad \lim_{t\to 0^+} e^{-t/\tau}=1}
\]
\[
\boxed{I_\infty=\dfrac{U_0}{R_1+R_2},\quad R_k=\dfrac{h_k}{\sigma_k A}}
\]

Derivation:
\[
\begin{align}
&\text{As } t\to\infty:\; I(t)\to A\,\frac{U_0 \sigma_1 \sigma_2}{b}
=\frac{U_0}{\frac{h_1}{\sigma_1 A}+\frac{h_2}{\sigma_2 A}}=\frac{U_0}{R_1+R_2}. 
\label{eq:limitinf} \tag{17}\\
&\text{As } t\to 0^+:\; I(0^+)=A\left[\frac{U_0 \sigma_1 \sigma_2}{b}
+\frac{U_0(\sigma_1 \varepsilon_2-\sigma_2 \varepsilon_1)^2 h_1 h_2}{a^2 b}\right],
\;\text{which is the steady conduction plus the displacement transient.}
\label{eq:limit0} \tag{18}
\end{align}
\]

### Final Answer
\[
\begin{align}
I(t)
&=A\,U_0\left[
\frac{\sigma_1 \sigma_2}{\sigma_1 h_2+\sigma_2 h_1}
+\frac{(\sigma_1 \varepsilon_2-\sigma_2 \varepsilon_1)^2\,h_1 h_2}{(\varepsilon_1 h_2+\varepsilon_2 h_1)^2\,(\sigma_1 h_2+\sigma_2 h_1)}
\,e^{-t/\tau}
\right],\\
\tau
&=\frac{\varepsilon_1 h_2+\varepsilon_2 h_1}{\sigma_1 h_2+\sigma_2 h_1}.
\end{align}
\]

# Refined Solution
### Problem Statement Explanation
We consider a closed, simple compressible system containing a fixed amount of a non-ideal gas whose empirical equation of state (EOS) is:
- p = k T^(3/2) V^(-4/5)

Here:
- p is the pressure of the gas,
- V is the volume of the gas,
- T is the absolute temperature,
- k is a positive constant characteristic of the gas.

We are told that the specific heat ratio γ = C_p / C_V is exactly a constant, independent of both temperature T and volume V.

Definitions:
- C_V is the heat capacity at constant volume for the fixed amount of gas,
- C_p is the heat capacity at constant pressure for the fixed amount of gas,
- γ ≡ C_p / C_V is assumed to be a constant independent of state.

Assumptions:
- The system is thermodynamically stable (e.g., (∂p/∂V)_T < 0), allowing use of standard thermodynamic identities,
- All thermodynamic functions are smooth, allowing use of partial derivatives and Maxwell relations.

Goal: Determine the numerical value of the constant γ implied by the given EOS and the assumption that γ is constant.

### Step 1
Principles/Original Formulas/Assumptions:
\[\boxed{C_p - C_V = -\,T\,\frac{\left[(\partial p/\partial T)_V\right]^2}{(\partial p/\partial V)_T}}\]
\[\boxed{p(T,V) = k\,T^{3/2}\,V^{-4/5}}\]

Derivation:
Compute the required partial derivatives of the EOS:
\[
\begin{align}
\left(\frac{\partial p}{\partial T}\right)_{V} 
&= \frac{3}{2}\,k\,T^{1/2}\,V^{-4/5}
\label{eq:dPdT} \tag{1} \\
\left(\frac{\partial p}{\partial V}\right)_{T} 
&= -\frac{4}{5}\,k\,T^{3/2}\,V^{-9/5}
\label{eq:dPdV} \tag{2}
\end{align}
\]
Substitute into the identity for C_p - C_V:
\[
\begin{align}
C_p - C_V 
&= -T\,\frac{\left[\left(\frac{3}{2}k T^{1/2} V^{-4/5}\right)\right]^2}{-\frac{4}{5}k T^{3/2} V^{-9/5}} \nonumber \\
&= T\,\frac{\frac{9}{4}k^2 T V^{-8/5}}{\frac{4}{5}k T^{3/2} V^{-9/5}} \nonumber \\
&= \frac{9}{4}\cdot\frac{5}{4}\,k\,T^{1/2}\,V^{1/5} \nonumber \\
&= \frac{45}{16}\,k\,T^{1/2}\,V^{1/5}
\label{eq:Cp_minus_Cv} \tag{3}
\end{align}
\]

### Step 2
Principles/Original Formulas/Assumptions:
\[\boxed{\gamma \equiv \frac{C_p}{C_V}}\]
\[\boxed{C_p - C_V = (\gamma-1)\,C_V}\]
\[\boxed{\gamma = \text{constant (independent of }T\text{ and }V\text{)}}\]

Derivation:
Use γ = C_p/C_V to rewrite C_p - C_V:
\[
\begin{align}
C_p - C_V = (\gamma - 1)\,C_V
\label{eq:gamma_relation} \tag{4}
\end{align}
\]
Combine \eqref{eq:Cp_minus_Cv} and \eqref{eq:gamma_relation} to express C_V(T,V):
\[
\begin{align}
(\gamma - 1)\,C_V &= \frac{45}{16}\,k\,T^{1/2}\,V^{1/5} \nonumber \\
\Longrightarrow\quad
C_V(T,V) &= \frac{45}{16}\,\frac{k\,T^{1/2}\,V^{1/5}}{\gamma - 1}
\label{eq:Cv_expr} \tag{5}
\end{align}
\]

### Step 3
Principles/Original Formulas/Assumptions:
\[\boxed{\left(\frac{\partial C_V}{\partial V}\right)_{T} = T\,\left(\frac{\partial^2 p}{\partial T^2}\right)_{V}}\]
\[\boxed{p(T,V) = k\,T^{3/2}\,V^{-4/5}}\]

Derivation:
Evaluate the right-hand side from the EOS:
\[
\begin{align}
\left(\frac{\partial p}{\partial T}\right)_{V} 
&= \frac{3}{2}\,k\,T^{1/2}\,V^{-4/5} \quad \text{(from \eqref{eq:dPdT})} \nonumber \\
\left(\frac{\partial^2 p}{\partial T^2}\right)_{V} 
&= \frac{3}{2}\cdot\frac{1}{2}\,k\,T^{-1/2}\,V^{-4/5}
= \frac{3}{4}\,k\,T^{-1/2}\,V^{-4/5} \nonumber \\
T\left(\frac{\partial^2 p}{\partial T^2}\right)_{V} 
&= \frac{3}{4}\,k\,T^{1/2}\,V^{-4/5}
\label{eq:RHS_identity} \tag{6}
\end{align}
\]
Evaluate the left-hand side using \eqref{eq:Cv_expr} and γ = const:
\[
\begin{align}
\left(\frac{\partial C_V}{\partial V}\right)_{T} 
&= \frac{45}{16}\,\frac{k\,T^{1/2}}{\gamma - 1}\,\left(\frac{\partial}{\partial V}V^{1/5}\right)_{T} \nonumber \\
&= \frac{45}{16}\,\frac{k\,T^{1/2}}{\gamma - 1}\,\left(\frac{1}{5}V^{-4/5}\right) \nonumber \\
&= \frac{9}{16}\,\frac{k\,T^{1/2}\,V^{-4/5}}{\gamma - 1}
\label{eq:LHS_identity} \tag{7}
\end{align}
\]
Equate \eqref{eq:LHS_identity} and \eqref{eq:RHS_identity} and solve for γ:
\[
\begin{align}
\frac{9}{16}\,\frac{k\,T^{1/2}\,V^{-4/5}}{\gamma - 1} 
&= \frac{3}{4}\,k\,T^{1/2}\,V^{-4/5} \nonumber \\
\Longrightarrow\quad \frac{9}{16}\,\frac{1}{\gamma - 1} &= \frac{3}{4} \nonumber \\
\Longrightarrow\quad \frac{1}{\gamma - 1} &= \frac{12}{9} = \frac{4}{3} \nonumber \\
\Longrightarrow\quad \gamma - 1 &= \frac{3}{4} \nonumber \\
\Longrightarrow\quad \gamma &= \frac{7}{4}
\label{eq:gamma_value} \tag{8}
\end{align}
\]

### Final Answer
\[
\begin{align}
\boxed{\gamma = \frac{7}{4}}
\end{align}
\]

# Refined Solution
### Problem Statement Explanation
We consider a charged particle constrained to move on an infinitely large horizontal plane described by polar coordinates (r, θ). A static magnetic field exists, directed vertically upward (perpendicular to the plane), with magnitude varying as
B(r) = m v / (q √(a r)),
where:
- a is a given positive constant with units such that ar has units of length,
- m and q are positive constants used in the field specification (not necessarily the particle’s own mass and charge),
- v is a given constant with units of speed, appearing only in B(r).

The particle itself has charge-to-mass ratio (q_p/m_p) = 3q / (2√2 m). It is launched from the origin r = 0 along the polar axis direction θ = 0 with initial speed v0, i.e.,
- at t = 0: r(0) = 0, θ(0) = 0,
- initial velocity is radially outward: ṙ(0) = v0, and the tangential speed r θ̇ at the origin is zero.

There is no electric field, and motion is nonrelativistic. We seek the polar trajectory r(θ).

### Step 1
Principles/Original Formulas/Assumptions
\[\boxed{\mathbf{F} = m_p \mathbf{a}}\]
\[\boxed{\mathbf{F} = q_p\, \mathbf{v} \times \mathbf{B}}\]
\[\boxed{a_r = \ddot r - r \dot\theta^{2}, \quad a_\theta = \frac{1}{r}\frac{d}{dt}\left(r^{2}\dot\theta\right)}\]

Derivation
\[
\begin{align}
&\text{Let } \mathbf{B} = B(r)\,\hat{\mathbf{k}} \text{ (upward), and } \mathbf{v} = \dot r\,\hat{\mathbf{e}}_r + r \dot\theta\,\hat{\mathbf{e}}_\theta.\nonumber\\
&\Rightarrow \mathbf{v}\times \mathbf{B} = B(r)\big(-\dot r\,\hat{\mathbf{e}}_\theta + r\dot\theta\,\hat{\mathbf{e}}_r\big).\nonumber\\
&\text{Radial component: } m_p(\ddot r - r\dot\theta^2) = q_p B(r)\, r \dot\theta,\label{eq:rad}\tag{1}\\
&\text{Azimuthal component: } m_p\frac{1}{r}\frac{d}{dt}(r^2\dot\theta) = -\, q_p B(r)\, \dot r.\label{eq:az}\tag{2}
\end{align}
\]

### Step 2
Principles/Original Formulas/Assumptions
\[\boxed{\frac{1}{r}\frac{d}{dt}(r^{2}\dot\theta) = -\,\frac{q_p}{m_p} B(r)\,\dot r}\]
\[\boxed{dr = \dot r\,dt}\]
\[\boxed{\frac{q_p}{m_p} = \frac{3q}{2\sqrt{2}\,m},\quad B(r) = \frac{m v}{q \sqrt{a r}}}\]

Derivation
\[
\begin{align}
&\text{From \eqref{eq:az}}:\quad \frac{1}{r}\frac{d}{dt}(r^{2}\dot\theta) = -\,\frac{q_p}{m_p} B(r)\,\dot r.\nonumber\\
&\text{Multiply by }dt \text{ and use } dr=\dot r\,dt:\quad \frac{1}{r}\,d(r^2\dot\theta) = -\,\frac{q_p}{m_p} B(r)\,dr.\nonumber\\
&\Rightarrow d(r^2\dot\theta) = -\,\frac{q_p}{m_p} B(r)\, r\,dr.\label{eq:exact}\tag{3}
\end{align}
\]
Insert the given expressions:
\[
\begin{align}
\frac{q_p}{m_p} B(r)\, r &= \frac{3q}{2\sqrt{2}m}\cdot \frac{m v}{q\sqrt{a r}} \cdot r
= \frac{3v}{2\sqrt{2}}\,\frac{\sqrt{r}}{\sqrt{a}}.\nonumber
\end{align}
\]
Hence
\[
\begin{align}
d(r^2\dot\theta) &= -\,\frac{3v}{2\sqrt{2}\,\sqrt{a}}\,\sqrt{r}\,dr
= -\,\frac{v}{\sqrt{2}\,\sqrt{a}}\,d\!\left(r^{3/2}\right).\label{eq:intstep}\tag{4}
\end{align}
\]
Integrating and using the launch condition (purely radial at r=0 implies r^2\dot\theta\to 0):
\[
\begin{align}
r^2\dot\theta &= -\,\frac{v}{\sqrt{2a}}\,r^{3/2} \quad \Rightarrow \quad \dot\theta = -\,\frac{v}{\sqrt{2 a\, r}}.\label{eq:thetadot}\tag{5}
\end{align}
\]

### Step 3
Principles/Original Formulas/Assumptions
\[\boxed{\frac{d}{dt}\left(\tfrac{1}{2}m_p v^2\right) = q_p\,\mathbf{v}\cdot(\mathbf{v}\times\mathbf{B}) = 0}\]
\[\boxed{v^2 = \dot r^{\,2} + (r\dot\theta)^2}\]

Derivation
\[
\begin{align}
&\text{Magnetic force does no work }\Rightarrow \text{speed is constant } v(t) = v_0.\nonumber\\
&\Rightarrow \dot r^{\,2} + (r\dot\theta)^2 = v_0^2.\label{eq:energy}\tag{6}
\end{align}
\]
Using \eqref{eq:thetadot} gives
\[
\begin{align}
r\dot\theta = -\,\frac{v}{\sqrt{2a}}\,\sqrt{r} \ \Rightarrow\ (r\dot\theta)^2 = \frac{v^2}{2a}\,r.\nonumber
\end{align}
\]
Thus
\[
\begin{align}
\dot r^{\,2} &= v_0^2 - \frac{v^2}{2a}\,r,\qquad \dot r = +\sqrt{\,v_0^2 - \frac{v^2}{2a}\,r\,}\ \ \text{(outward branch initially)}.\label{eq:rdot}\tag{7}
\end{align}
\]

### Step 4
Principles/Original Formulas/Assumptions
\[\boxed{\frac{dr}{d\theta} = \frac{\dot r}{\dot\theta}}\]

Derivation
\[
\begin{align}
\frac{dr}{d\theta} &= \frac{\dot r}{\dot\theta}
= \frac{+\sqrt{\,v_0^2 - \frac{v^2}{2a}r\,}}{-\,\dfrac{v}{\sqrt{2ar}}}
= -\,\sqrt{2ar}\,\frac{\sqrt{\,v_0^2 - \frac{v^2}{2a}r\,}}{v}.\nonumber\\
\text{Define } r_* &\equiv \frac{2a\,v_0^2}{v^2} \ \Rightarrow\ \frac{dr}{d\theta} = -\,\sqrt{\,r\,(r_* - r)\,}.\label{eq:drdtheta}\tag{8}
\end{align}
\]

### Step 5
Principles/Original Formulas/Assumptions
\[\boxed{\text{Use } r=\frac{R}{2}(1-\cos\phi)\ \Rightarrow\ \sqrt{r(R-r)}=\frac{R}{2}|\sin\phi|,\ \ dr=\frac{R}{2}\sin\phi\,d\phi}\]
\[\boxed{1-\cos\phi=2\sin^2(\phi/2),\quad \text{and on } \phi\in[0,\pi],\ \sin\phi\ge 0}\]

Derivation
\[
\begin{align}
&\text{From \eqref{eq:drdtheta}}:\quad d\theta = -\,\frac{dr}{\sqrt{r(r_*-r)}}.\nonumber\\
&\text{Substitute } r = \frac{r_*}{2}(1-\cos\phi)\ (\Rightarrow \phi:0\to\pi\ \text{as } r:0\to r_*):\ \sqrt{r(r_*-r)}=\frac{r_*}{2}\sin\phi,\ dr=\frac{r_*}{2}\sin\phi\,d\phi.\nonumber\\
&\Rightarrow d\theta = -\,\frac{\frac{r_*}{2}\sin\phi\,d\phi}{\frac{r_*}{2}\sin\phi} = -\,d\phi.\label{eq:dthetadphi}\tag{9}
\end{align}
\]
With θ(0)=0 at r=0 corresponding to φ=0, integration gives
\[
\begin{align}
\theta = -\,\phi.\label{eq:theta_phi}\tag{10}
\end{align}
\]
Thus
\[
\begin{align}
r(\theta) &= \frac{r_*}{2}\big(1-\cos\phi\big) = \frac{r_*}{2}\big(1-\cos\theta\big),\qquad \theta\in[-\pi,0]\ \text{(outward branch)}.\label{eq:rtheta_branch}\tag{11}
\end{align}
\]

### Step 6
Principles/Original Formulas/Assumptions
\[\boxed{r_* = \frac{2a\,v_0^2}{v^2}}\]

Derivation
\[
\begin{align}
r(\theta) &= \frac{1}{2}\left(\frac{2a\,v_0^2}{v^2}\right)\big(1-\cos\theta\big)
= \frac{a\,v_0^2}{v^2}\,\big(1-\cos\theta\big),\qquad \theta\in[-\pi,0].\label{eq:final_form}\tag{12}
\end{align}
\]
This polar curve continues periodically, yielding a closed cardioid-shaped trajectory that reaches a turning point at θ = -π (r = r_*) and returns to the origin at θ = -2π, consistent with the conserved speed and the derived θ̇.

### Final Answer
\[
\begin{align}
\boxed{\,r(\theta) = \frac{a\,v_0^2}{v^2}\,\big(1-\cos\theta\big)\,,\quad \text{with the physically realized launch branch } \theta\in[-\pi,0].\,}
\end{align}
\]

# Refined Solution
### Problem Statement Explanation
We model a typhoon as an axisymmetric, isothermal, rigidly rotating cylindrical column of singly ionized monoatomic ideal gas at uniform temperature T0, rotating with angular velocity vector ω⃗ = ω ẑ. The column has radius R and height H with H ≫ R. The plasma species are:
- Positive ions (mass mN ≈ atomic mass after losing one electron),
- Free electrons (mass me),

with at most one electron released per atom. Under the stated strong ionization and confinement, we take full single ionization so that the total number of ions and the total number of electrons each equals the original number of atoms N (Ni = Ne = N). Both species are confined within the cylinder; end effects are negligible due to H ≫ R.

Interactions among charged species are neglected, and the influence of the internal electric potential on the equilibrium density profiles is neglected (the problem permits using k = ω^2/(2 kB T0) to simplify results). The permittivity of free space is ε0. A finite radial charge separation resulting from differing mass distributions of ions and electrons produces a radial electric field E(r) r̂. The breakdown field Em is the threshold for lightning but is not needed for the UAV dynamics.

A UAV of volume V (with V1/3 ≪ R), mass m, and electric charge q0 operates at radius r0, co-rotating with angular speed ω. The UAV can thrust only vertically (to balance weight), thus no radial or azimuthal thrust is available. At t = 0, a small radial perturbation imparts a small radial velocity v0 (with v0 ≪ ω r0). Small-amplitude periodic radial oscillations (often described as epicyclic precession) are observed. We are to find the precession angular frequency Ω (expressible in terms of q0 and r0, with other given parameters as needed).

Assumptions and modeling choices:
- Ideal-gas behavior for each species at uniform T0.
- When determining equilibrium density profiles, electric forces are neglected as instructed.
- Axisymmetry with no z-dependence (H ≫ R), allowing the use of an infinite-cylinder approximation for Gauss’s law.
- Radial pressure gradient exerts a net force −V ∇p on the small UAV (buoyancy-like, with negligible drag).
- Gravity is balanced by vertical thrust and does not enter radial dynamics.

### Step 1
Principles/Original Formulas/Assumptions
\[\boxed{\frac{dp_s}{dr}=\rho_s(r)\,\omega^2 r \quad \text{(Euler balance in steady rigid rotation per species, neglecting electric force as instructed)}}\]
\[\boxed{p_s(r)=n_s(r)\,k_B T_0 \quad \text{(ideal gas, isothermal)}}\]
\[\boxed{\rho_s(r)=m_s\,n_s(r)}\]
\[\boxed{k=\frac{\omega^2}{2k_B T_0}}\]

Derivation
For each species s (ions: s=+, m+=mN; electrons: s=−, m−=me), the steady rotational balance with the stated neglect of electric forces yields
\[
\begin{align}
\frac{dp_s}{dr}&=\rho_s\,\omega^2 r,\quad p_s=n_s k_B T_0,\quad \rho_s=m_s n_s. \label{eq:Euler}\tag{1}
\end{align}
\]
Thus
\[
\begin{align}
k_B T_0 \frac{dn_s}{dr}&=m_s n_s \omega^2 r \nonumber\\
\frac{1}{n_s}\frac{dn_s}{dr}&=\frac{m_s \omega^2}{k_B T_0} r=2 m_s k\,r,\quad k=\frac{\omega^2}{2k_B T_0}. \label{eq:dn}\tag{2}
\end{align}
\]
Integrating from 0 to r,
\[
\begin{align}
\ln n_s(r)-\ln n_s(0)&=\int_0^r 2 m_s k r' \,dr'=m_s k r^2 \nonumber\\
n_s(r)&=A_s\,e^{m_s k r^2},\quad A_s\equiv n_s(0). \label{eq:n_profile}\tag{3}
\end{align}
\]

### Step 2
Principles/Original Formulas/Assumptions
\[\boxed{N=\int_V n_s(\mathbf r)\,dV \quad \text{(each species number equals }N\text{ by confinement and single ionization)}}\]
\[\boxed{\int_0^R r\,e^{\alpha r^2}\,dr=\frac{1}{2\alpha}\left(e^{\alpha R^2}-1\right)\quad(\alpha>0)}\]

Derivation
Normalize n_s(r) over the cylinder (height H, radius R) to N:
\[
\begin{align}
N&=\int_0^H\!dz\int_0^{2\pi}\!d\phi\int_0^R\! n_s(r)\,r\,dr
=2\pi H A_s \int_0^R r\,e^{m_s k r^2}\,dr \nonumber\\
&=2\pi H A_s \cdot \frac{1}{2 m_s k}\left(e^{m_s k R^2}-1\right). \label{eq:Nnorm}\tag{4}
\end{align}
\]
Solve for A_s:
\[
\begin{align}
A_s=\frac{N\,m_s\,k}{\pi H\left(e^{m_s k R^2}-1\right)}. \label{eq:A}\tag{5}
\end{align}
\]
Hence
\[
\begin{align}
n_s(r)&=\frac{N\,m_s\,k}{\pi H\left(e^{m_s k R^2}-1\right)}\,e^{m_s k r^2}, \label{eq:ns}\tag{6}\\
\rho_s(r)&=m_s n_s(r)=\frac{N\,m_s^2\,k}{\pi H\left(e^{m_s k R^2}-1\right)}\,e^{m_s k r^2}. \label{eq:rhos}\tag{7}
\end{align}
\]

### Step 3
Principles/Original Formulas/Assumptions
\[\boxed{\rho_{\mathrm{ch}}(r)=e\,[n_+(r)-n_-(r)]}\]
\[\boxed{\oint \mathbf E\cdot d\mathbf a=\frac{Q_{\mathrm{enc}}}{\varepsilon_0} \quad \text{(Gauss’s law; infinite-cylinder approximation for }H\gg R\text{)}}\]

Derivation
The charge density is
\[
\begin{align}
\rho_{\mathrm{ch}}(r)&=e\left(n_+(r)-n_-(r)\right)
=\frac{e N k}{\pi H}\left[\frac{m_N e^{m_N k r^2}}{e^{m_N k R^2}-1}-\frac{m_e e^{m_e k r^2}}{e^{m_e k R^2}-1}\right]. \label{eq:rhoch}\tag{8}
\end{align}
\]
Using a coaxial Gaussian cylinder of radius r and length L, Gauss’s law gives
\[
\begin{align}
E(r)\,2\pi r L&=\frac{1}{\varepsilon_0}\int_0^r \rho_{\mathrm{ch}}(r')\,2\pi r' L\,dr' \nonumber\\
E(r)&=\frac{1}{\varepsilon_0 r}\int_0^r \rho_{\mathrm{ch}}(r')\,r'\,dr' \nonumber\\
&=\frac{e N}{2\pi \varepsilon_0 H\,r}\left[\frac{e^{m_N k r^2}-1}{e^{m_N k R^2}-1}-\frac{e^{m_e k r^2}-1}{e^{m_e k R^2}-1}\right]. \label{eq:Er}\tag{9}
\end{align}
\]

### Step 4
Principles/Original Formulas/Assumptions
\[\boxed{p(r)=\sum_s p_s(r)=\sum_s n_s(r)\,k_B T_0}\]
\[\boxed{\rho(r)=\sum_s \rho_s(r)=\sum_s m_s n_s(r)}\]
\[\boxed{\frac{dp}{dr}=\rho(r)\,\omega^2 r \quad \text{(sum of Eq. \eqref{eq:Euler} over species)}}\]

Derivation
Summing Eq. \eqref{eq:Euler} over s = +, − (ions and electrons) yields the total pressure gradient balance in rigid rotation:
\[
\begin{align}
\frac{dp}{dr}=\rho(r)\,\omega^2 r. \label{eq:dp_total}\tag{10}
\end{align}
\]
From Eqs. \eqref{eq:ns}–\eqref{eq:rhos},
\[
\begin{align}
p(r)&=(n_+(r)+n_-(r))\,k_B T_0, \nonumber\\
\rho(r)&=\frac{N k}{\pi H}\left[\frac{m_N^2 e^{m_N k r^2}}{e^{m_N k R^2}-1}+\frac{m_e^2 e^{m_e k r^2}}{e^{m_e k R^2}-1}\right]. \label{eq:p_rho}\tag{11}
\end{align}
\]

### Step 5
Principles/Original Formulas/Assumptions
\[\boxed{a_r=\ddot r - r\,\dot\theta^2 \quad \text{(radial component of acceleration in polar coordinates, inertial frame)}}\]
\[\boxed{m\,a_r=\sum F_r \quad \text{(Newton’s second law, radial component)}}\]
\[\boxed{F_{E,r}=q_0\,E(r),\quad F_{p,r}=-V\,\frac{dp}{dr}}\]

Derivation
The net radial force on the UAV equals the electric force plus the pressure-gradient force. Thus, with no azimuthal or radial thrust,
\[
\begin{align}
m\big(\ddot r - r\,\dot\theta^2\big)&=q_0 E(r)-V\,\frac{dp}{dr}. \label{eq:radial_inertial}\tag{12}
\end{align}
\]
For the reference circular motion at r = r0 with θ̇ = ω and r̈ = 0,
\[
\begin{align}
m(0-\omega^2 r_0)&=q_0 E(r_0)-V\,\frac{dp}{dr}\Big|_{r_0}. \label{eq:balance0}\tag{13}
\end{align}
\]
Using Eq. \eqref{eq:dp_total} gives the steady circular balance
\[
\begin{align}
-m\,\omega^2 r_0&=q_0 E(r_0)-V\,\rho(r_0)\,\omega^2 r_0. \label{eq:balance}\tag{14}
\end{align}
\]
For q0 = 0 this implies neutral “centrifugal buoyancy” m = V ρ(r0); for q0 ≠ 0 the electric force supplies the remainder.

### Step 6
Principles/Original Formulas/Assumptions
\[\boxed{L_z=m r^2 \dot\theta=\text{const.} \quad \text{(no azimuthal forces act on the UAV)}}\]
\[\boxed{m\,\ddot r=\frac{L_z^2}{m r^3}+q_0 E(r)-V\,\rho(r)\,\omega^2 r \quad \text{(using } \frac{dp}{dr}=\rho\omega^2 r\text{)}}\]
\[\boxed{r=r_0+\delta r,\ \ |\delta r|\ll r_0 \quad \text{(small-oscillation linearization)}}\]

Derivation
Because only radial forces act, the azimuthal torque vanishes and Lz = m r^2 θ̇ is conserved. From Eq. \eqref{eq:radial_inertial} and Eq. \eqref{eq:dp_total},
\[
\begin{align}
m\,\ddot r = m r \dot\theta^2 + q_0 E(r) - V\,\rho(r)\,\omega^2 r
= \frac{L_z^2}{m r^3} + q_0 E(r) - V\,\rho(r)\,\omega^2 r. \label{eq:radial_exact}\tag{15}
\end{align}
\]
For the circular orbit, Lz = m r0^2 ω. Let r = r0 + δr with |δr| ≪ r0. Expand to first order:
\[
\begin{align}
\frac{L_z^2}{m r^3} &= \frac{(m r_0^2 \omega)^2}{m (r_0+\delta r)^3}
= m \omega^2 r_0 - 3 m \omega^2 \delta r + \mathcal O(\delta r^2), \label{eq:centrif_exp}\tag{16}\\
E(r_0+\delta r)&=E(r_0)+E'(r_0)\,\delta r + \mathcal O(\delta r^2), \nonumber\\
\rho(r_0+\delta r)&=\rho(r_0)+\rho'(r_0)\,\delta r + \mathcal O(\delta r^2). \label{eq:Taylor}\tag{17}
\end{align}
\]
Insert these into Eq. \eqref{eq:radial_exact} and use Eq. \eqref{eq:balance} to cancel the constant terms:
\[
\begin{align}
m\,\ddot{\delta r} &= \Big[-3 m \omega^2 + q_0 E'(r_0) - V\,\omega^2\big(\rho'(r_0) r_0+\rho(r_0)\big)\Big]\,\delta r. \label{eq:lin}\tag{18}
\end{align}
\]
Thus δr̈ + Ω^2 δr = 0 with
\[
\begin{align}
\Omega^2 &= 3 \omega^2 - \frac{q_0}{m} E'(r_0) + \frac{V \omega^2}{m}\Big(\rho'(r_0) r_0+\rho(r_0)\Big). \label{eq:Omega_general}\tag{19}
\end{align}
\]
The initial radial velocity v0 sets only the oscillation amplitude, not Ω.

### Step 7
Principles/Original Formulas/Assumptions
\[\boxed{E(r)=\frac{e N}{2\pi \varepsilon_0 H\,r}\left[\frac{e^{m_N k r^2}-1}{e^{m_N k R^2}-1}-\frac{e^{m_e k r^2}-1}{e^{m_e k R^2}-1}\right]}\]
\[\boxed{\rho(r)=\frac{N k}{\pi H}\left[\frac{m_N^2 e^{m_N k r^2}}{e^{m_N k R^2}-1}+\frac{m_e^2 e^{m_e k r^2}}{e^{m_e k R^2}-1}\right]}\]
\[\boxed{\frac{d}{dr}\left(\frac{f(r)}{r}\right)=\frac{f'(r)}{r}-\frac{f(r)}{r^2}}\]

Derivation
Define
\[
\begin{align}
f_s(r)\equiv \frac{e^{m_s k r^2}-1}{e^{m_s k R^2}-1},\qquad s\in\{N,e\}. \label{eq:fs}\tag{20}
\end{align}
\]
Then E(r) = C [fN(r) − fe(r)]/r with C = e N/(2π ε0 H). Differentiate:
\[
\begin{align}
E'(r)&=C\left(\frac{f_N'(r)-f_e'(r)}{r}-\frac{f_N(r)-f_e(r)}{r^2}\right), \quad
f_s'(r)=\frac{2 m_s k r\,e^{m_s k r^2}}{e^{m_s k R^2}-1}. \label{eq:Eprime}\tag{21}
\end{align}
\]
So
\[
\begin{align}
E'(r_0) &= \frac{e N}{2\pi \varepsilon_0 H}\Bigg\{2k\left[\frac{m_N e^{m_N k r_0^2}}{e^{m_N k R^2}-1}-\frac{m_e e^{m_e k r_0^2}}{e^{m_e k R^2}-1}\right]
-\frac{1}{r_0^2}\left[\frac{e^{m_N k r_0^2}-1}{e^{m_N k R^2}-1}-\frac{e^{m_e k r_0^2}-1}{e^{m_e k R^2}-1}\right]\Bigg\}. \label{eq:Eprime_final}\tag{22}
\end{align}
\]
From Eq. \eqref{eq:rhos},
\[
\begin{align}
\rho(r)&=\frac{N k}{\pi H}\left[\frac{m_N^2 e^{m_N k r^2}}{e^{m_N k R^2}-1}+\frac{m_e^2 e^{m_e k r^2}}{e^{m_e k R^2}-1}\right], \nonumber\\
\rho'(r)&=\frac{N k}{\pi H}\left[\frac{2 m_N^3 k r\, e^{m_N k r^2}}{e^{m_N k R^2}-1}+\frac{2 m_e^3 k r\, e^{m_e k r^2}}{e^{m_e k R^2}-1}\right]. \label{eq:rho_prime}\tag{23}
\end{align}
\]
Therefore,
\[
\begin{align}
\rho'(r_0) r_0 + \rho(r_0) = \frac{N k}{\pi H}\left[\frac{(2 k m_N r_0^2 + 1)\,m_N^2 e^{m_N k r_0^2}}{e^{m_N k R^2}-1}+\frac{(2 k m_e r_0^2 + 1)\,m_e^2 e^{m_e k r_0^2}}{e^{m_e k R^2}-1}\right]. \label{eq:rho_combo}\tag{24}
\end{align}
\]
Substituting Eqs. \eqref{eq:Eprime_final} and \eqref{eq:rho_combo} into Eq. \eqref{eq:Omega_general} yields a closed-form Ω^2:
\[
\begin{align}
\Omega^2
&= 3\omega^2 - \frac{N e\,q_0}{2\pi m\,H\,\varepsilon_{0}\,r_0^2}
\left[\frac{(2k m_{N}r_{0}^2 - 1)\,e^{m_{N}k r_{0}^2} + 1}{e^{m_{N}k R^2} - 1}
- \frac{(2k m_{e}r_{0}^2 - 1)\,e^{m_{e}k r_{0}^2} + 1}{e^{m_{e}k R^2} - 1}\right] \nonumber\\
&\qquad {} + \frac{k N V\omega^2}{\pi m H}\left[\frac{(2k m_{N}r_{0}^2 + 1)\,m_{N}^2\,e^{m_{N}k r_{0}^2}}{e^{m_{N}k R^2} - 1}
+ \frac{(2k m_{e}r_{0}^2 + 1)\,m_{e}^2\,e^{m_{e}k r_{0}^2}}{e^{m_{e}k R^2} - 1}\right], \label{eq:Omega_explicit}\tag{25}
\end{align}
\]
with k = ω^2/(2 kB T0).

### Final Answer
\[
\begin{align}
\boxed{\Omega^2
= 3 \omega^2 - \frac{q_0}{m}\,E'(r_0) + \frac{V \omega^2}{m}\Big(\rho'(r_0) r_0+\rho(r_0)\Big),}
\end{align}
\]
where
\[
\begin{align}
E'(r_0) &= \frac{e N}{2\pi \varepsilon_0 H}\Bigg\{2k\left[\frac{m_N e^{m_N k r_0^2}}{e^{m_N k R^2}-1}-\frac{m_e e^{m_e k r_0^2}}{e^{m_e k R^2}-1}\right]
-\frac{1}{r_0^2}\left[\frac{e^{m_N k r_0^2}-1}{e^{m_N k R^2}-1}-\frac{e^{m_e k r_0^2}-1}{e^{m_e k R^2}-1}\right]\Bigg\}, \\
\rho(r_0) &= \frac{N k}{\pi H}\left[\frac{m_N^2 e^{m_N k r_0^2}}{e^{m_N k R^2}-1}+\frac{m_e^2 e^{m_e k r_0^2}}{e^{m_e k R^2}-1}\right], \\
\rho'(r_0) r_0 + \rho(r_0) &= \frac{N k}{\pi H}\left[\frac{(2 k m_N r_0^2 + 1)\,m_N^2 e^{m_N k r_0^2}}{e^{m_N k R^2}-1}+\frac{(2 k m_e r_0^2 + 1)\,m_e^2 e^{m_e k r_0^2}}{e^{m_e k R^2}-1}\right],
\end{align}
\]
and k = ω^2/(2 kB T0). Equation \eqref{eq:Omega_explicit} provides an equivalent single closed-form expression.
